# Documentation Folder Guidelines

This folder is intended to contain all project-related documentation required for design understanding, verification planning, testcase tracking, and project maintenance.

## Purpose

The `docs/` directory is used to organize all technical and verification documentation associated with the project.

This includes:

* Design specifications
* Verification plans
* Testcase plans
* Coverage plans
* Assertion plans
* Version tracking documents

Maintaining proper documentation ensures consistent verification methodology, easier collaboration, and long-term maintainability of the project.

## Recommended Structure

```text id="kqtdhk"
docs/
 ├── specs/
 │    ├── design_spec.pdf
 │    └── protocol_spec.pdf
 │
 ├── verification_plan/
 │    ├── verification_plan.docx
 │    └── verification_plan.pdf
 │
 ├── testcase_plan/
 │    ├── testcase_plan.xlsx
 │    ├── tb_architecture
 │    └── block_diagram
 │
 └── README.md
```

## Testcase Plan Guidelines

The `testcase_plan.xlsx` file should contain multiple sheets to organize verification tracking information clearly.

### Recommended Excel Sheets

| Sheet Name        | Description                                   |
| ----------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| Testcases         | List of all planned and implemented testcases |
| Coverage Plan     | Functional coverage goals and coverage points |
| Assertion Plan    | Assertion definitions and verification checks |
| Feature Mapping   | Mapping between DUT features and testcases    |
| Regression Status | Pass/fail status tracking for regressions     |
| Version History   | Document revision history and updates         |

## Rules and Guidelines

* Only project-related documentation should be placed inside this folder.
* Specifications should be stored in read-only/reference format whenever possible.
* Verification plans should clearly define:

  * Verification scope
  * Methodology
  * Features to verify
  * Coverage goals
* Testcase plans should maintain traceability between:

  * Specifications
  * Features
  * Assertions
  * Coverage points
  * Testcases
* All documentation should follow version control practices and maintain revision history.

## Naming Convention

Use clear and descriptive naming conventions.

Examples:

* `design_spec.pdf`
* `verification_plan.docx`
* `testcase_plan.xlsx`

## Objective

Maintaining a structured documentation directory improves:

* Requirement traceability
* Verification planning
* Team collaboration
* Review efficiency
* Project maintainability
* Verification completeness tracking

A well-organized documentation structure ensures that all verification activities remain aligned with design requirements and project goals.

